The perpich case did not establish the definition of "militia" as a whole. It simply defined the National guard as a portion of the "active militia", drawn from the general population of the state, which comprises the militia as a whole. The court did concur that it might be unconstitutional for the federal governmetn to require active duty training by a truly state milita, the National Gaurd is an extension of the federal guard, although not on active duty unless needed. 

 In the maryland case, the National gaurd is defined as the militia as defined by the article 1 of the constitution. It is strongly implied, however, that the definition of "militia" as used in article one, and the definition of the same word in the second amendment may be different. This is obvious in the fact that the text of the decision specifically states that 

 //quote//
 The national Guard is the modern Militia reserved to the States by Art. I. 8, cl. 15, 16, of the Constitution
 //quote//

 It does not say "the national guard is the modern militia reserved to the states by the constitution"

 Here are the relevant clasues from the constitution:

 //quote//
 Clause 15: To provide for calling forth the Militia to execute the Laws of the Union, suppress Insurrections and repel Invasions; 

 Clause 16: To provide for organizing, arming, and disciplining, the Militia, and for governing such Part of them as may be employed in the Service of the United States, reserving to the States respectively, the Appointment of the Officers, and the Authority of training the Militia according to the discipline prescribed by Congress; 
 //end quote//

 The definition, as laid out by this case, only applies to those 2 clauses of the constitution. No where else. Specifically, it does not neccesarily apply to the definition of militia as used in the second amendment. The only supreme court decision which has ever addressed that is Miller.

 And, of course the comprised is past tense, they were citing historical reference. How else would you phrase a statement like that when discussing historical references?

 The big question as to the second amendment is, does the first phrase mean anything at all? Several legal documents of the period ere written in that format. There is an introductory clause, then the main phrase. You can argue this all you want, but that is the way it is. This was a common writing method in use at the time. Textbooks which have survived from the time teach this writing style, although they refered to it as a "purpose clause" as opposed to an "introdutory clause"

 Some other examples:

 From the Rhode Island constitution:
 //quote//
 "The liberty of the press being essential to the security of freedom in a state, any person may publish sentiments on any subject, being responsible for the abuse of that liberty."
 //end quote//

 This passage would seem to ensure the freedom of speech. By using the second amendment argument argument that the first statement is the main statement, however, it does not. That clause would limit free speech to that which is directly connected to the security of freedom. By that thinking, discussion of recipes, cars, the weather, or the price of tea could be prohibited.

 Another example from the New Hampshire constitution:
 //quote//
 "Economy being a most essential virtue in all states, especially in a young one; no pension shall be granted, but in consideration of actual services, and such pensions ought to be granted with great caution, by the legislature, and never for more than one year at a time."
 //end quote//

 This amendment is commonly held to make pensions of longer than one yer at a time void. However, if you apply the forementioned method of thinking, it would only apply to the state when it was "young".

 If you want some more examples of this, look up "Volokh". He provides dozens of examples form state constitutions.

 Ultimatly, what needs to be done in order to solve the second amendment question is to put it directly to the supreme court. Anytime a second amendment case comes up, though, both sides of the issue do their best to torpedo it. This is why I am no longer a supporter of the NRA, or of HCI. I am an American, and I believe in our system of government. I want to see this hit the supreme court, as is proper with constitutional questions, and I will resign myself to whatever decision the court makes. That is how America is supposed to work.
